{"title_page": "Waianae Sugar Company", "text_new": "The '''Waianae Sugar Company''', founded in 1878, was the first major sugar plantation on [[Oahu]], [[Hawaii]].\n\n== History ==\n\nIn 1878, Judge [[Hermann A. Widemann|Hermann Widemann]] planted his first crop in [[Waianae, Hawaii|Wai'anae]], eleven years before the creation of the [[Oahu Railway and Land Company]], and seventeen years before the [[Oahu Railway and Land Company|OR&L]] would reach the sugar mill. Waianae Sugar Company's plantation cultivated land in three valleys, [[M\u0101kaha, Hawaii|Makaha]], [[Lualualei, Hawaii|Lualualei]], and [[Waianae, Hawaii|Wai'anae]]. Having a {{track gauge|2ft6in|lk=on}} [[Narrow-gauge railway|narrow gauge]] railway line, it was the only sugar plantation on the island whose tracks could not connect to the OR&L's tracks. Despite struggles for water, this company lasted 69 years, closing down in 1947, the same year as the Oahu Railway's closure.\n\nBy 1890, sugar cane was planted on 600 acres with a yield of 2,500 tons. The company had 350 workers and three locomotives to transport the cane over 12 miles of narrow gauge track.<ref name=\"Book\">{{cite magazine| first=J. David| last=Book| url=http://www.pkcc.org/images/pdf/A_Place_Called_Echoing_Hills.pdf| title=A Place Called Pu\u2019u Kahea (Echoing Hills)| magazine=Vermont Volunteer| date=Winter 2014| pages=2-3}}</ref>\n\n== Locomotives ==\nThe first locomotive was imported from [[John Fowler & Co.]] at [[Leeds]], England. It had to be disassembled and re-assembled to get it ashore. Only then it was noted that it did not match the {{track gauge|2ft6in}} narrow gauge track. The undercarriage had to be dismantled, machined to size, and then commissioned.<ref name=\"Book\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Coord|21.4424364|-158.1862819|display=title}}<!--The mill stood apparently directly in front of the present Protestant Church on 85-946 Mill Street in Waianae.-->\n{{Hawaii railroads}}\n\n\n[[Category:Sugar companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies based in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Waianae Range]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Honolulu County, Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Defunct Hawaii railroads]]\n[[Category:Sugar mill railways]]\n[[Category:Narrow gauge railroads in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:2 ft 6 in gauge railways in the United States]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies established in 1878]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies disestablished in 1947]]\n[[Category:Railway companies established in 1878]]\n[[Category:Railway companies disestablished in 1947]]\n[[Category:1878 establishments in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:1947 disestablishments in Hawaii]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Waianae Sugar Company''', founded in 1878, was the first major sugar plantation on [[Oahu]], [[Hawaii]].\n\n== History ==\n\nIn 1878, Judge [[Hermann A. Widemann|Hermann Widemann]] planted his first crop in [[Waianae, Hawaii|Wai'anae]], eleven years before the creation of the [[Oahu Railway and Land Company]], and seventeen years before the [[Oahu Railway and Land Company|OR&L]] would reach the sugar mill. Waianae Sugar Company's plantation cultivated land in three valleys, [[M\u0101kaha, Hawaii|Makaha]], [[Lualualei, Hawaii|Lualualei]], and [[Waianae, Hawaii|Wai'anae]]. Having a {{TrackGauge|2ft6in|lk=on}} [[Narrow-gauge railway|narrow gauge]] railway line, it was the only sugar plantation on the island whose tracks could not connect to the OR&L's tracks. Despite struggles for water, this company lasted 69 years, closing down in 1947, the same year as the Oahu Railway's closure.\n\nBy 1890, sugar cane was planted on 600 acres with a yield of 2,500 tons. The company had 350 workers and three locomotives to transport the cane over 12 miles of narrow gauge track.<ref name=\"Book\">{{cite magazine| first=J. David| last=Book| url=http://www.pkcc.org/images/pdf/A_Place_Called_Echoing_Hills.pdf| title=A Place Called Pu\u2019u Kahea (Echoing Hills)| magazine=Vermont Volunteer| date=Winter 2014| pages=2-3}}</ref>\n\n== Locomotives ==\nThe first locomotive was imported from [[John Fowler & Co.]] at [[Leeds]], England. It had to be disassembled and re-assembled to get it ashore. Only then it was noted that it did not match the {{TrackGauge|2ft6in}} narrow gauge track. The undercarriage had to be dismantled, machined to size, and then commissioned.<ref name=\"Book\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Coord|21.4424364|-158.1862819|display=title}}<!--The mill stood apparently directly in front of the present Protestant Church on 85-946 Mill Street in Waianae.-->\n{{Hawaii railroads}}\n\n\n[[Category:Sugar companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies based in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Waianae Range]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Honolulu County, Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Defunct Hawaii railroads]]\n[[Category:Sugar mill railways]]\n[[Category:Narrow gauge railroads in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:2 ft 6 in gauge railways in the United States]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies established in 1878]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies disestablished in 1947]]\n[[Category:Railway companies established in 1878]]\n[[Category:Railway companies disestablished in 1947]]\n[[Category:1878 establishments in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:1947 disestablishments in Hawaii]]\n", "name_user": "Slambo", "label": "safe", "comment": "bypass template redirects", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Waianae_Sugar_Company"}
{"title_page": "Border ware", "text_new": "[[File:16th_century_Border_Ware_tall_jug.jpg|thumb|16th century Border ware jug]]\n\n'''Border ware''' is a type of post-medieval [[Great Britain|British]] pottery commonly used in [[London]] during the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries. The lead-glazed, sandy earthenware was produced from kilns along the border between [[Hampshire]] and [[Surrey]]. There are two classes of Border ware, fine whitewares and fine redwares. \n\n==History==\nBorder ware evolved from a medieval pottery known as [[Surrey whiteware]]. Surrey whiteware consisted of four classes: [[Kingston upon Thames|Kingston-type]] ware, Coarse Border ware, [[Cheam]] whiteware  and Tudor Green ware. The earlier whitewares were produced from the 13th to the 16th centuries.{{sfn|Vince|1985|p=76}}{{sfn|Pearce|1988|p=7}}\n\nBorder ware was manufactured in the Surrey-Hampshire border area from the 16th century to the 19th centuries, although the whitewares were produced only during the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries. The  demand for whitewares declined during the 17th century while the demand for redwares increased..{{sfn|Holling|1971|p=64}} The production of whitewares ended most likely during the early 18th century; Redwares continued to be produced until the 19th century.{{sfn|Pearce|1992|p=1}}\n\n==Description==\n[[File:16th_century_Border_ware_flask.jpg|thumb|Border ware flask, 16th century]]\nThe term, \"Border ware\" was introduced by [[Archaeologist|archaeologist]], Clive Orton, to describe the lead-glazed, sandy earthenware produced along the Surrey-Hampshire borders during the early post-medieval period. The pottery is divided into two classes, whitewares and redwares, although the term \"Border ware\" generally refers to the whitewares. The redwares are known as \"Red Border ware.{{sfn|Pearce|1992|p=1}}\n\n===Fabrics===\nWhiteware fabrics are generally hard with a smooth and fine texture. Fabric colours include off-white, yellow, brown, buff, olive and pinkish grey. Glazes are often [[Crazing|crazed]] and finishes range from thin and spotty to thick and glossy. Glaze colours include yellow, brown, olive clear, and green.{{sfn|Pearce|1992|p=5}}\n\nRedware fabrics range from smooth to slightly rough in feel. Fabric colours generally range from brick red to reddish-yellow. Finishes range from thin and uneven to thick and glossy. A clear lead glaze was often used, giving the pottery products an orange or reddish-brown colour. Other glaze colours include olive, brown and green. Green glaze was created by potters by adding copper to lead glaze.{{sfn|Pearce|1992|p=6}}\n\n===Forms===\nPottery products were traditional household items commonly used during the post-medieval period.{{sfn|Holling|1971|p=69}} [[Skillet|Skillets]], saucepans, chafing dishes and [[Pipkin|tripod pipkins]] were common cookware products manufactured by the Border ware pottery industry.\n[[File:Border_ware_porridger_yellow-glaze.jpg|thumb|left||Border ware porringer]]\nBorder ware forms used for serving and storing food begin with dishes, which are divided into flanged dishes and deep dishes. Bowls were manufactured in a wide variety of shapes and sizes: wide bowls, deep bowls, bowls with handles, and [[Porringer|porringers]]. Vessels for storing and serving liquids include drinking [[Jug|jugs]], [[Cup|cups]], goblets and [[Mug|mugs]]. \n\nOther Border ware forms include costrels (portable flasks), which can be divided into two categories, mammiform costrels and bottle shaped costrels. [[Candlestick|Candlesticks]] were two styles: upright and saucer. There were also [[Lantern|lanterns]], [[Chamber pot|chamber pots]], [[Tudor money box|money boxes]], [[Jar|jars]], double dishes, [[Whistle|whistles]], fuming pots and [[Colander|strainers]].\n\n==Production==\n{{Quote box\n|width     =15em\n|border    = 2px\n|align     = right\n|bgcolor   = #FFFACD\t\t\n|fontsize  = 85%\n|title_bg  =\n|title_fnt =\n|title     =\n|quote     = \"The Hampshire-Surrey border potters had a natural advantage through an accident of geology which is not repeated in other areas near London north of the Thames, nor in Kent, and it applied to every kind of vessel they produced.\"\n|salign    = right\n|source=\u2014 ''F.W. Holling'', 1971.{{sfn|Holling|1971|p=65}}}}\n\n===Clay Sources===\n\nThe source of the white-firing clays used to produce Surrey whitewares was the [[Reading Formation|Reading Beds]] along the borders of Hampshire and [[Berkshire]]. The Reading beds between [[Farnham]] and [[Tongham]] were the best source of potting clay for medieval potters producing wares for the London market. These outcrops of white-firing and red-firing clay deposits had provided an abundant source of clays for pottery manufacturing since the early [[Roman Britain|Roman period]].{{sfn|Pearce|1992|p=3}}\n\n===Pottery sites===\nBorder ware manufacturing sites were selected for their proximity to plentiful clay and fuel supplies.{{sfn|Holling|1971|p=63}}\nThe area northeast of [[Farnham]] became the center of the Border ware pottery industry. Three sites have been identified as producing the pottery best representing Border Ware fabrics, forms and glazes. These sites are: ''Farnborough Hill Convent'' in [[Farnborough, Hampshire|Farnborough]], Hampshire, Ye Old Malthouse in [[Hawley, Hampshire|Hawley]], Hampshire and ''The Lime'', [[Ash]], Surrey.{{sfn|Pearce|1992|p=2}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Stamford ware]]\n*[[Surrey whiteware]]\n*[[Humber ware]]\n*[[Bartmann jug]]\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=150px heights=150px perrow=6\">\nBorder ware jar green-glaze.jpg||Green-glazed Border ware jar \nBorder ware candlestick.jpg|Border ware candlestick \nBorder_ware_small_bowl.jpg|Border ware bowl\nBorder_ware_jug.jpg| Border ware jug\nBorder_ware_pipkin_green-glazed.jpg|Border ware pipkin\nKingston-type_jug_round.jpg||Surrey whiteware \n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite journal |last1=Holling |first1=F.W. |title=A preliminary note on the pottery industry of the Hampshire-Surrey Borders |journal=Surrey Archaeological Collections |date=1971 |volume=68 |pages=57-88|url=https://archaeologydataservice.ac.uk/archives/view/surreyac/contents.cfm?vol=68 |accessdate=4 April 2020|ref=harv}} \n\n*{{cite book|last1=Pearce|first1=Jaqueline ||last2=Vince|first2=Alan |title=Surrey Whitewares\n|year=1988|isbn= 978-0903290340|location=London |publisher=London & Middlesex Archaeological societies |ref=harv}}\n\n*{{cite book|last1=Pearce|first1=Jaqueline |title=Border Wares. Post-Medieval Pottery in London 1500-1700|year=1992|isbn=978-0112904946|location=London |publisher=Museum of London |ref=harv}}\n\n*{{cite journal |last1=Vince |first1=A.G. |title=The Saxon and Medieval Pottery of London: A Review |journal=Journal of Medieval Archaeology |date=1985 |volume=29 |pages=29-83 |url=https://archaeologydataservice.ac.uk/archiveDS/archiveDownload?t=arch-769-1/dissemination/pdf/vol29/29_025_093.pdf |accessdate=4 April 2020|ref=harv}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |last1=Laing |first1=Lloyd |title=Pottery in Britain 4000 BC to AD 1900 |date=2003 |publisher=Greenlight Publishing |isbn=978-1897738146}} \n*{{cite book |last1=McCarthy |first1=Michael |last2=Brooks |first2=Catherine M. |title=Medieval Pottery in Britain, Ad 900-1600 |date=1995 |publisher=Leicester University Press |isbn=978-0718512712}} \n\n==External links==\n*[http://friendsofwhitehallcheam.co.uk/index.php/past-events/ The Time Cheam Project]\n\n{{Pottery}}\n \n[[Category:British pottery]]\n[[Category:16th century in England]]\n[[Category:17th century in England]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:16th_century_Border_Ware_tall_jug.jpg|thumb|16th century Border ware jug]]\n\n'''Border ware''' is a type of post-medieval [[Great Britain|British]] pottery commonly used in [[London]] during the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries. The lead-glazed, sandy earthenware was produced from kilns along the border between [[Hampshire]] and [[Surrey]]. There are two classes of Border ware, fine whitewares and fine redwares. \n\n==History==\nBorder ware evolved from a medieval pottery known as [[Surrey whiteware]]. Surrey whiteware consisted of four classes: [[Kingston upon Thames|Kingston-type]] ware, Coarse Border ware, [[Cheam]] whiteware  and Tudor Green ware. The earlier whitewares were produced from the 13th to the 16th centuries.{{sfn|Vince|1985|p=76}}{{sfn|Pearce|1988|p=7}}\n\nBorder ware was manufactured in the Surrey-Hampshire border area from the 16th century to the 19th centuries, although the whitewares were produced only during the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries. The  demand for whitewares declined during the 17th century while the demand for redwares increased..{{sfn|Holling|1971|p=64}} The production of whitewares ended most likely during the early 18th century; Redwares continued to be produced until the 19th century.{{sfn|Pearce|1992|p=1}}\n\n==Description==\n[[File:16th_century_Border_ware_flask.jpg|thumb|Border ware flask, 16th century]]\nThe term, \"Border ware\" was introduced by [[Archaeologist|archaeologist]], Clive Orton, to describe the lead-glazed, sandy earthenware produced along the Surrey-Hampshire borders during the early post-medieval period. The pottery is divided into two classes, whitewares and redwares, although the term \"Border ware\" generally refers to the whitewares. The redwares are known as \"Red Border ware.{{sfn|Pearce|1992|p=1}}\n\n===Fabrics===\nWhiteware fabrics are generally hard with a smooth and fine texture. Fabric colours include off-white, yellow, brown, buff, olive and pinkish grey. Glazes are often [[Crazing|crazed]] and finishes range from thin and spotty to thick and glossy. Glaze colours include yellow, brown, olive clear, and green.{{sfn|Pearce|1992|p=5}}\n\nRedware fabrics range from smooth to slightly rough in feel. Fabric colours generally range from brick red to reddish-yellow. Finishes range from thin and uneven to thick and glossy. A clear lead glaze was often used, giving the pottery products an orange or reddish-brown colour. Other glaze colours include olive, brown and green. Green glaze was created by potters by adding copper to lead glaze.{{sfn|Pearce|1992|p=6}}\n\n===Forms===\nPottery products were traditional household items commonly used during the post-medieval period.{{sfn|Holling|1971|p=69}} [[Skillet|Skillets]], saucepans, chafing dishes and [[Pipkin|tripod pipkins]] were common cookware products manufactured by the Border ware pottery industry.\n[[File:Border_ware_porridger_yellow-glaze.jpg|thumb|left||Border ware porringer]]\nBorder ware forms used for serving and storing food begin with dishes, which are divided into flanged dishes and deep dishes. Bowls were manufactured in a wide variety of shapes and sizes: wide bowls, deep bowls, bowls with handles, and [[Porringer|porringers]]. Vessels for storing and serving liquids include drinking [[Jug|jugs]], [[Cup|cups]], goblets and [[Mug|mugs]]. \n\nOther Border ware forms include costrels (portable flasks), which can be divided into two categories, mammiform costrels and bottle shaped costrels. [[Candlestick|Candlesticks]] were two styles: upright and saucer. There were also [[Lantern|lanterns]], [[Chamber pot|chamber pots]], [[Tudor money box|money boxes]], [[Jar|jars]], double dishes, [[Whistle|whistles]], fuming pots and [[Colander|strainers]].\n\n==Production==\n{{Quote box\n|width     =15em\n|border    = 2px\n|align     = right\n|bgcolor   = #FFFACD\t\t\n|fontsize  = 85%\n|title_bg  =\n|title_fnt =\n|title     =\n|quote     = \"The Hampshire-Surrey border potters had a natural advantage through an accident of geology which is not repeated in other areas near London north of the Thames, nor in Kent, and it applied to every kind of vessel they produced.\"\n|salign    = right\n|source=\u2014 ''F.W. Holling'', 1971.{{sfn|Holling|1971|p=65}}}}\n\n===Clay Sources===\n\nThe source of the white-firing clays used to produce Surrey whitewares was the [[Reading Formation|Reading Beds]] along the borders of Hampshire and [[Berkshire]]. The Reading beds between [[Farnham]] and [[Tongham]] were the best source of potting clay for medieval potters producing wares for the London market. These outcrops of white-firing and red-firing clay deposits had provided an abundant source of clays for pottery manufacturing since the early [[Roman Britain|Roman period]].{{sfn|Pearce|1992|p=3}}\n\n===Pottery sites===\nBorder ware manufacturing sites were selected for their proximity to plentiful clay and fuel supplies.{{sfn|Holling|1971|p=63}}\nThe area northeast of [[Farnham]] became the center of the Border ware pottery industry. Three sites have been identified as producing the pottery best representing Border Ware fabrics, forms and glazes. These sites are: ''Farnborough Hill Convent'' in [[Farnborough]], Hampshire, Ye Old Malthouse in [[Hawley]], Hampshire and ''The Lime'', [[Ash]], Surrey.{{sfn|Pearce|1992|p=2}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Stamford ware]]\n*[[Surrey whiteware]]\n*[[Humber ware]]\n*[[Bartmann jug]]\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=150px heights=150px perrow=6\">\nBorder ware jar green-glaze.jpg||Green-glazed Border ware jar \nBorder ware candlestick.jpg|Border ware candlestick \nBorder_ware_small_bowl.jpg|Border ware bowl\nBorder_ware_jug.jpg| Border ware jug\nBorder_ware_pipkin_green-glazed.jpg|Border ware pipkin\nKingston-type_jug_round.jpg||Surrey whiteware \n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite journal |last1=Holling |first1=F.W. |title=A preliminary note on the pottery industry of the Hampshire-Surrey Borders |journal=Surrey Archaeological Collections |date=1971 |volume=68 |pages=57-88|url=https://archaeologydataservice.ac.uk/archives/view/surreyac/contents.cfm?vol=68 |accessdate=4 April 2020|ref=harv}} \n\n*{{cite book|last1=Pearce|first1=Jaqueline ||last2=Vince|first2=Alan |title=Surrey Whitewares\n|year=1988|isbn= 978-0903290340|location=London |publisher=London & Middlesex Archaeological soc